definition.value: A wax that is naturally synthesized by a plant or animal.

value.value: A white or colourless soft solid derivable from petroleum, coal or oil shale, that consists of a mixture of hydrocarbon molecules containing between twenty and forty carbon atoms.
An organic-rich fine-grained sedimentary rock containing kerogen from which liquid hydrocarbons called shale oil can be produced.
A drainage process during which water is transported away from peat.

Any liquid, liquefiable, or mastic composition that, after application to a substrate in a thin layer, converts to a solid film. It is most commonly used to protect, color, or provide texture to objects.
Paint that contains lead.
A planned process that is the movement of people, animals and goods from one location to another.
the residue powder that is derived from the combustion of wood.
Ash that is produced from the burning of coal.
A very fine, powdery material composed mostly of silica made from the burning of finely ground coal in a boiler.
a coarse, angular ash particle that is too large to be carried up into the smoke stacks so it forms in the bottom of the coal furnace.
molten bottom ash from slag tap and cyclone type furnaces that turns into pellets that have a smooth glassy appearance after it is cooled with water.

definition.value: a material leftover from the process of reducing sulfur dioxide emissions from a coal-fired boiler that can be a wet sludge consisting of calcium sulfite or calcium sulfate or a dry powered material that is a mixture of sulfites and sulfates.

value.value: A human construction which serves as a memorial.

definition.value: Monuments can commemorate people, animals, populations, events, or any other entity.

value.value: A human construction which is used to initiate and control a fission nuclear chain reaction or nuclear fusion reactions.
A nuclear reactor which uses a neutron moderator to slow neutrons until they approach the average kinetic energy of the surrounding particles.
A nuclear reactor in which the fission chain reaction is sustained by fast neutrons.

definition.value: Fast neutrons are neutrons carrying energies above 0.5 MeV or greater, on average. They are defined as in opposition to thermal neutrons used in thermal-neutron reactors.

value.value: A nuclear reactor which serves primarily as a neutron source for purposes other than power.

definition.value: An example use of a research nucelar reactor is the production of radioisotopes for medicine and industry
Research reactors are simpler than power reactors and operate at lower temperatures. They need far less fuel, and far less fission products build up as the fuel is used

value.value: A nuclear reactor which is used as a source of power.
Soil which is located in a mangrove biome.

definition.value: Mangrove soils are typically saline, anoxic, acidic and frequently waterlogged.

value.value: A spring that is located in the desert.
An environmental material which is unable to resist shear forces and continuously deforms when subject to them.

definition.value: A human construction which is used to process materials into forms that have increased value or utility in downstream processes.

value.value: A refinery which is capable of processing petroleum oil.

definition.value: Petroleum processing is an industrial process  in which crude oil is transformed and refined into useful products such as petroleum naphtha, gasoline, diesel fuel, asphalt base, heating oil, kerosene, liquefied petroleum gas, jet fuel and fuel oils.

value.value: A refinery which is capable of processing raw sugar. Raw sugar is processed from cane or beets into white refined sugar.

A refinery which is capable of processing natural gas. Natural-gas processing encompasses a range of industrial processes designed to purify raw natural gas by removing impurities, contaminants and higher molecular mass hydrocarbons to produce what is known as pipeline quality dry natural gas
A lake underneath the surface of the Earth.
A planned process which has the intention of producing, consuming, or transforming materials via the execution of chemical reactions.
A planned material transformation process which takes as input a material and removes impurities.

definition.value: A chemical engineering process that produces ammonia en masse via artificial nitrogen fixation.
This process is the primary synthetic means of producing fertilizer

value.value: A chemical engineering process which generates hydrogen gas.

definition.value: A mineral deposit that contains uranium ore.

value.value: A uranium deposit where self-sustaining nuclear chain reactions have occurred.

definition.value: Oklo is the only known location for this in the world and consists of 16 sites at which self-sustaining nuclear fission reactions are thought to have taken place approximately 1.7 billion years ago, and ran for a few hundred thousand years, averaging probably less than 100 kW of thermal power during that time
Sediment that is part of a mangrove biome.
Mangroves are widely recognised as key ecosystems for climate change mitigation as they capture and store significant amounts of sediment organic carbon (SOC).
Sediment that is part of a salt marsh.
Solid material that has a waste role.
A dairy farm which is managed using practices certified to be organic by a competent authority.

value.value: A landfill that receives household waste.

label.value: biological nutrient removal during wastewater treatment

definition.value: A recycling process that uses microbes for the uptake of nitrogen and phosphorus during wastewater treatment.
A process in which includes the components of an environmental system as participants.
This is a convenience class for organisation and should not be used for annotation.

value.value: A type of land degradation in which terrestrial ecosystem becomes increasingly dry, typically losing its bodies of water as well as vegetation and wildlife.

A general and temporary condition of partial or complete inundation of normally dry land areas from the overflow of inland and/or tidal waters, and/or the unusual and rapid accumulation or runoff of surface waters from any source. A great flow along a watercourse or a flow causing inundation of lands not normally covered by water.

definition.value: A process which occurs within an atmosphere.
This class will be populated by inference and is primarily organisational.

value.value: A process by which thermal radiation from a planetary surface is absorbed by atmospheric greenhouse gases, and is re-radiated in all directions. Since part of this re-radiation is back towards the surface and the lower atmosphere, it results in an elevation of the average surface temperature above what it would be in the absence of the gases.
A process which diminishes the functioning of an ecosystem located on land.

definition.value: This could include, for example, reducing soil health, pollinator activity, or an ecosystem's ability  to sequester carbon.
A process which consists of all photosynthesis processes instantiated in an ecosystem.
A process which consists of all respiration processes instantiated in an ecosystem.
